<instruction>

<response format>
Provide your answer with these fields.
- suspicious_frags: The list of suspicious code fragments in the code.
It should contain only the code fragments exists in the code. If you do not find any suspicious code fragments, return an empty list for suspicious_frags
- explanation: The explanation of why other code fragments should NOT be investigated.
It is very important to not miss any suspicious code fragments, so please give a sufficient explanation why other code fragments should not be investigated.
DO NOT give any explanation for the selected suspicious code fragments.
</response format>
<target_code>
Here is the code of UtList_Add:
```c
void UtList_Add(UtListHead_t *ListHead, void *Data, uint32 DataSize, uint32 Tag)
{
    UtListNode_t *TagHead;
    UtListNode_t *NewNode;

    TagHead = UtList_GetHead(ListHead, Tag);
    if (TagHead != NULL)
    {
        NewNode      = UtList_NewNode(Data, DataSize);
        NewNode->Tag = Tag;
        UtList_Insert_Before(TagHead, NewNode);
    }
}
```
</target_code>
Please find suspicious code fragments in the code and report them. Other agents can not investigate other fragments that you do not report, so it is very important to find all suspicious fragments without missing any. Report the suspicious fragments AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE.
explanation: No syntactically unreachable code is present in the provided function. All statements are potentially reachable: the assignment to TagHead is executed unconditionally; the three statements inside the if-block are executed when the runtime condition (TagHead != NULL) holds. There are no constant boolean expressions, no statements following an unconditional return, no labels/gotos that skip code, and no infinite loops that would render subsequent code unreachable. (Note: potential runtime issues such as dereferencing a NULL NewNode returned by UtList_NewNode are defects but are not instances of unreachable code and therefore do not fall under MISRA C 2023 Rule 2.1.)
